Instead of writing all logic directly in the file, we usually create a main() function.

Wrong way:
    print("Program started")
    name = input("Enter name: ")
    print(f"Hello {name}")

Better way:
    def main():
        print("Program started")
        name = input("Enter name: ")
        print(f"Hello {name}")

    if __name__ == "__main__":
        main()

The file says:

    if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()

Python does not force you to write main(), but in real projects it is a good habit.